Check my earlier reply to Steve for related entries.

@Mike 

As long as you espresso remorse, all is forgiven.




Even by the emus

@Mike 
As I understand it, it's a real grind.


Beans for the emus...

@Bonnie 

A long time ago, I read somewhere that the Japanese are horrified by the idea of using and reusing a handkerchief and much prefer to carry a small packet of tissues. 

Yes, handkerchiefs can be gross, but they are often more convenient than disposable tissues. Especially if one doesn’t carry a purse.

@Andrew 

Thank you so much for this excellent bit of CRAPPER trivia.  These days I only occasionally read the comments for reasons that I'll keep to myself.  But I am very pleased that I checked in and found this. 

Thank youu

@MAR1 I am about 9 months into NYT crosswords, having only done Wordles for a couple of years prior. 
I knew early on that Mondays were easy and they rolled through the week with greater difficulty. I now do Mondays without look-ups, almost Tuesdays too. Every other days requires help to different degrees, but rather than a cheat, I consider them learning, as I know I have come a long way. 
As an Aussie, I get stuck on many Americanised themes and words (sports, politics and geography mainly), my two weeks in NY and Conn, have only mildly helped. But time has taught me nuances and new words and I surprise myself how quickly I get some now.

@John Deal 

I am right there with you. My average Saturday is just over 20 minutes and I struggled with this for an hour and 9! I have never been so off of the wavelength of an nyt puzzle.

Still completely solvable and after climbing out of the ring with this puzzle I think I enjoyed it?

@Vislander 
The Earth is slightly flattened at the poles (this was an exciting discovery in the late 1950's, as I recall 7th grade Science)....and ECUADOR is famously equatorial.... as you noted.  
One girl was particularly adamant that the Earth was 'pear-shaped'....and that was her nickname for the rest of the school year.  I can see her face in my mind's eye, but I can't remember her actual name......

@Minuteman 

I did note it, but did not take issue.  I guess I figured it was close enough for crosswords since they were going for the play on words.

Here emu, play with this.

@Times Rita 
I expect to need some cheating on a Saturday.  But THIRTY???  This was insane.  If I thought I knew an answer, I had to still check.  The 'bit of greenery in a rock garden' that I was SO SURE was 'moss', nope! (I got Ernst, as well.)  

Yes, continued good wishes for Will's health.

@Paul Turner 
Who knows?
Possibly you aren't particularly strong in visual memory, and are coming up against it in Crosswords, where it's a slight disadvantage.

@Elizabeth 
I've never seen one...  and we were regular orchard-goers back in the day.  

Hmm, I just noticed my knit sweater is on wrong-side out.  DHubby didn't notice it at all, of course.  Just one more sign of deterioration..... emphasis on OLE....

@Kevin 

Often it's about the constructor's wavelength - I've only been doing these puzzles for 9 or 10 months, and the only issues I had today were with some of the trivia, which I simply did not know, and one or two words that were new to me. Otherwise it was a somewhat tough but enjoyably clued puzzle. 

However, on some days - even the odd Tuesday! - I struggle with puzzles that most people fly through.

